items.name: Anime Style Negative Embedding for DreamShaper 4
items.description:
When activating this five vector negative embedding in your negative prompt it should help you attain an anime style more easily when using the checkpoint DreamShaper 4. The activation word by default is "anime-style-negative-embedding", but I recommend you change the file name to whatever word you want, as the filename is the activation word.

The embedding is probably fine to use on a variety of checkpoints, but the training images were generated on the DreamShaper 4 checkpoint and the embedding was also trained on it, so that is where to expect the best results.

The training images were generated with the use of the bad-artist and bad-artist-anime negative embeddings- they are good negative embeddings. They are at this hugging face repository if you want to download them.

modelVersions.name: First Release
modelVersions.description:
I created different vector versions of the embedding- from one to five vectors, and a 75 vector version. After doing far too many x/y/z plots, I determined that the best version for the intended use was the Five Vector version that was trained until step 500 at a batch size of 4 using the "d-adaptation" learning algo, and used the cosine annealing learning rate scheduler at a cycle of 1000 steps with 50 warmup steps. AdamW was enabled and left at default settings. The extension I used to train the embedding is this extension for A1111 WebUI.

You can checkout all the other versions if near the download button you click the arrow, and then click "training data". Five vectors at 500 steps "won" because the other version were either too baked (too many steps) or the differences were negligible. I tried to train until 5000 steps, but sometimes google colab would error out around the 4000-5000 step mark, which lead to a few of embeddings not having a 4500 or 5000 step version. The .optim files are included if you are interesting in resuming training on one of the embeddings.

There were 5000 training images that were used, though since the "chosen" version was trained until step 500 at batch 4, that means only 2000 of the images contributed the training of that embedding. If you are interested in the training images, I have them uploaded as a separate "version" called "Actual Training Images".

modelVersions.name: Actual Training Images
modelVersions.description: Download this if you want to use the training images to train the embedding using your own training parameters. Preview images are selected to give an idea of what the entire set contains. The image generation parameters for the set are in the generation details for the preview images. It should be the same across the board.

In addition, VAE uses stable-780000.

You can get better results by using HD redrawing. The parameters are

Size: 512x640 Denoising strength: 0.6

Hires upscale: 1.5, Hires upscaler: ESRGAN_4x

items.name: Yoshiie Style LoCon
items.description:
V1:

A LoRA for Yoshiie's Style based on YesMix.

Shouldn't need any trigger words, however adding 'yoshiie' or 'yoshiie style', forces the style more. Works best at weight 0.8-1.0. Clip Skip 2, however it is not required to generate good images. For best results, or results similar to mine, please use YesMix. Additionally, it is most recommended to use EasyNegative textual inversion.

Should work fine with other LoRAs.

Examples done using YesMix. Follow prompts to attempt replication and use given negatives for better generations.

Usage:

  • CFG Scale: 7-9

  • LoRA Weight: 0.6-0.8, 1.0 may default to giving text or greyscale, so add negatives

  • Should work fine for less detailed prompts. High-res fix is highly recommended

  • Trigger: yoshiie style

items.name: Kizuki - Anime / Hentai Checkpoint
items.description:
I have set up a Discord-Server where we can share images / ideas / prompts and help each other out. Also, if you have a LoRA request, feel free to ask me there.

If you want to support my work or gain early access / exclusive loras feel free to check out my Patreon or Ko-Fi.

Attention! V3 Update Notes:

First of all, thanks for all the downloads and likes so far.

The goal of this Version 3 this time was:

  • Adjusting artstyle further towards my "ideal"

  • Improving the age issue

  • Improving eye clarity

  • Improving details in general

Known Issues so far: Hands got worse than in v2 & white clothing will apear looking "wet"

If you like the artstye of Version 2 more, you don't have to switch to Version 3!

Further infos about the checkpoint / settings and stuff down below!

______________________________________________________________

Kizuki Mix

I really enjoyed discovering stable diffusion, and because of this community, I really got great results out of it.

But as someone who likes to tinker around and personalize things, I wanted to try creating my own Checkpoint and LoRA's.

And because this great community has given me so much, I wanted to give something back.

Keep in mind, this mix is made with NSFW related content in mind!

Prompts to get started

Prompt: best quality, masterpiece

Negative: (worst quality: 1.4), (low quality: 1.4),

* Adjust the strength and prompts to your liking, but keep in mind that the negative prompts are very important!

** Use (nsfw:value) positive/negative prompt as needed.

*** Consider adding tags like: anime, semi-realistic, realistic

Settings to use

Most samplers work pretty well, so try out what works for you and pick your favorite.

I'm personally a huge fan of DDIM because it's very fast and I can test prompts and seeds very quickly and make adjustments without much delay.

My "personal" basic settings:

Sampler: DDIM

Steps: 30

Clipskip: 2

CFG Scale: 10

VAE: Included in Checkpoint

HiRes fix: R-ESRGAN 4x+ Anime6B

HiRes Steps: 25

HiRes Denoise: 25

Upscale by 1x for prompt or seed testing and higher for final results.

Embeddings:

Sometimes they can help your results a lot, but they can also screw you over. So try adding or removing them from your prompts for different results.

Easy Negative

bad prompt

bad hands

bad artist

Loras:

Most of them should work out pretty well, but I would suggest to start with low values like 0.1/0.2 start increasing until you get the result you want.

Special thanks:

Unfortunately, I did not keep track of every resource author I used when I first started mixing and testing... Therefore, credit and huge thanks to all my fellow Civitai creators!

This is " BLACK SUN "

[LORA counterpart is here]

A deep study i will reference many many times over and over during " JOHNSON'S DIFFUSION CRASH COURSE ". This has been miticulously retrained from the same dataset, in many ways and with slight changes to the methodology or technology used to train. This will be a way to see the effects that those changes have made. All will be explained in time, however if you are following my Crash Course, you will benefit from playing around with these locally to interact with the training.

Each Resource in this set can be used interchangeably and in parallel so your can learn the effects in a controlled way.

This forms a Deep Study into Dreambooth Fine Tuning and LORA Dreambooth, with or without Deepbooru, BLIP and BLIP2 captioning.
Effective methods of Image Curation for datasets is also covered and this collection will expand into LOCON/LYCORIS and other methods as they appear.

Thanks for reading. Check the Version notes for more information !


note: owing to the scale of this educational project, more accurate demo images will be added soon, however these do reflect what can be achieved as this project is meant for mixing with other models and a FULLSTACK of LORA's (as shown in the current demo pics ;)

items.name: Dwarf Diffision
items.description:
Trained without a text encoder to make shadowrun dwarves on a handcrafted collection on images this Lora is more versatile than the original intent. Essentially it works to do the following things: reduce height, bulk up the body and face, gives pointy ears. With some effort you might be able to do other short fantasy races (gnomes, halflings, etc), but my success in that area has not been reliable so far.

Prompting:

1) Shadowrun dwarves: Add "dwarf, short, stocky, broad shoulders, pointy ears" to positive prompt, "furry, pointy ears, elf ears, dwarf ears, cat ears, horns, tusks" to negative. Experiment on weights depending on the model.

2) Fantasy dwarves: Add "dwarf, short, stocky, broad shoulders" to positive prompt, "pointy ears, horns, tusks" to negative. Experiment on weights depending on the model.

Do note that full body shots can be tricky to pull off. I recommend starting with my succesful prompts from examples.

General negative prompting advice: (nude, shirtless, nudity, nipples:1.5) to avoid unintended nudity. For female characters add (beard, man:1.2) too. Sometimes closes eyes on non-realistic models, tag (eyes wide open:1.7) or so to fix

Style and Models: Meant for use with Realistic Vision 1.3 and Deliberate, but seems to work with the most checkpoints I tried to various extents. All examples are straight txt2img. Here are recommended weights for checkpoints I tested:

Works well with Realistic Vision (0.7-0.9), Deliberate V2 (0.7-0.9), Dreamshaper V4 (0.5-0.8), , expmixLine_v20 (0.7-1.1), RevAnimated_v1.1 (0.7-1.1), Chilloutmix (0.8-1).

Technically works, but requires quite a bit of effort with Anything V3 and V4 (0.7-1.3) and AOM3 0.7-1.1 .

Does not work at all with RPG v4 and Dalcefo models. Works when merged into RPG v4 via Supermerger.

Settings: Works best at low to mid CFG (2.5-5), I personally prefer to pick lower end of the scale. Seems to mix with other Loras just fine.

items.name: djz Black Sun [LORA] [DEEP STUDY]
items.description:
This is " BLACK SUN "

[CKPT counterpart is here]

A deep study i will reference many many times over and over during " JOHNSON'S DIFFUSION CRASH COURSE ". This has been meticulously retrained from the same dataset, in many ways and with slight changes to the methodology or technology used to train. This will be a way to see the effects that those changes have made. All will be explained in time, however if you are following my Crash Course, you will benefit from playing around with these locally to interact with the training.

Each Resource in this set can be used interchangeably and in parallel so your can learn the effects in a controlled way.

This forms a Deep Study into Dreambooth Fine Tuning and LORA Dreambooth, with or without Deepbooru, BLIP and BLIP2 captioning.
Effective methods of Image Curation for datasets is also covered and this collection will expand into LOCON/LYCORIS and other methods as they appear.

Thanks for reading. Check the Version notes for more information !


note: owing to the scale of this educational project, more accurate demo images will be added soon, however these do reflect what can be achieved as this project is meant for mixing with other models and a FULLSTACK of LORA's (as shown in the current demo pics ;)

Mila Azul (born January 12th, 1997) is a Ukrainian adult model. Azul started her modeling career in 2016 at age 19 and has done fitness, lingerie, fashion, and nude art modeling, she came into the Adult Entertainment Industry in 2017 at the age of 20 and did her first shot for Film Studio ‘The Score Group’. If you like my work, a review is more than welcome! Also, follow me on Twitter or Instagram!

Looking for something... spicy? Here's my Patreon!

Also, I recently started a blog where I will gather resources and tutorials about my work here!

Hello there! Today I am happy to present my textual inversion of Mila Azul. I used 60 images of her, with a 7100 steps process. I wanted to experiment a bit this time because I used only one of her sets. Hope you'll like it! To use it in your works:

  • like Eva Elfie's textual inversion, this one is also particularly horny 😂 check the examples for some inspiration about the prompt;

  • download the file and place it into stable-diffusion-webui>embeddings folder;

  • add milazul97 to your prompt;

  • keep the sampling steps around 20, and CFG around 7 seems to work well. Great results with DPM++ SDE Karras & Realistic Vision. Face restore could help sometimes, especially when the image is not a close-up/portrait. Check the gallery for some inspiration!
